05237nam a22007335i 9780824864453DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20062006hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248644537 a10.1515/97808248644532doi  a(DE-B1597)484484  a(OCoLC)1018046289  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBQ568.N675bV45 2006eb 7aREL0070202bisacsh04a294.3095932221 aVeidlinger, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpreading the Dhamma :bWriting, Orality, and Textual Transmission in Buddhist Northern Thailand /cDaniel Veidlinger. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSoutheast Asia: Politics, Meaning, and Memory ;v6100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on transliteration and translation -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Monks and Memory: The Oral World -- t2. Early Thai Encounters with Orality and Literacy -- t3. Golden Age, Golden Images, and Golden Leaves -- t4. The Text in the World: Scribes, Sponsors, and Manuscript Culture -- t5. Turning Over a New Leaf: The Advance of Writing -- t6. Overlooked or Looked Over? The Meaning and Uses of Written Pali Texts -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow did early Buddhists actually encounter the seminal texts of their religion? What were the attitudes held by monks and laypeople toward the written and oral Pali traditions? In this pioneering work, Daniel Veidlinger explores these questions in the context of the northern Thai kingdom of Lan Na. Drawing on a vast array of sources, including indigenous chronicles, reports by foreign visitors, inscriptions, and palm-leaf manuscripts, he traces the role of written Buddhist texts in the predominantly oral milieu of northern Thailand from the fifteenth to the nineteenth centuries.Veidlinger examines how the written word was assimilated into existing Buddhist and monastic practice in the region, considering the use of manuscripts for textual study and recitation as well as the place of writing in the cultic and ritual life of the faithful. He shows how manuscripts fit into the economy, describes how they were made and stored, and highlights the understudied issue of the "cult of the book" in Theravâda Buddhism. Looking at the wider Theravâda world, Veidlinger argues that manuscripts in Burma and Sri Lanka played a more central role in the preservation and dissemination of Buddhist texts.By offering a detailed examination of the motivations driving those who sponsored manuscript production, this study draws attention to the vital role played by forest-dwelling monastic orders introduced from Sri Lanka in the development of Lan Na’s written Pali heritage. It also considers the rivalry between those monks who wished to preserve the older oral tradition and monks, rulers, and laypeople who supported the expansion of the new medium of writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBuddhismzThailand, NorthernxHistory. 0aCommunicationxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aPali literaturezThailand, NorthernxHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486445340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824864453423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter